-- TRACK 5: ACADEMIC SUCCESS
-- =============================================

  (
    '44444444-0005-0001-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000005',
    'Study Habits That Actually Work',
    E'STUDY HABITS THAT ACTUALLY WORK\n\nMost students study wrong. They re-read notes, highlight, and cram — all of which are scientifically shown to be ineffective. Here is what actually works.\n\nTHE PROBLEM WITH PASSIVE STUDY:\nRe-reading and highlighting feel productive but create the illusion of learning. You recognize the information when you see it, but you cannot recall it on your own — which is what tests require.\n\nACTIVE RECALL:\nInstead of re-reading your notes, close them and try to recall everything you just learned. Write it down from memory. This is the single most effective study technique — proven by decades of research.\n\nSPACED REPETITION:\nStudying the same material multiple times over days and weeks is far more effective than cramming. Your brain strengthens the memory each time you retrieve it.\n\nRule: Review new material within 24 hours, then again after 3 days, then after a week.\n\nTHE POMODORO TECHNIQUE:\n1. Set a timer for 25 minutes\n2. Focus on ONE task with zero distractions\n3. When timer rings, take a 5-minute break\n4. After 4 rounds, take a 20-30 minute break\n\nThis works because your brain needs regular rest to consolidate learning.\n\nELIMINATE DISTRACTIONS:\nStudying with your phone in the room reduces your effective IQ by up to 10 points — even if you never pick it up. Phone in another room. Notifications off.\n\nTHE STUDY ENVIRONMENT:\n- Consistent location (brain associates place with focus)\n- Good lighting\n- No background TV\n- Comfortable but not too comfortable\n\nASK FOR HELP EARLY:\nIf you are lost in a class, do not wait until the day before the test. Go to the teacher, ask a classmate, watch a YouTube tutorial. The longer you wait, the bigger the gap.\n\nATTEND CLASS:\nThis sounds obvious, but attendance is the single strongest predictor of grades. You cannot learn what you miss.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- How do you currently study? Is it working?\n- What is your biggest distraction when trying to focus?\n- What subject do you need to get help in right now?',
    1, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0005-0002-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000005',
    'College Prep & Your Next Step',
    E'COLLEGE PREP & YOUR NEXT STEP\n\nCollege is one option — but every path forward requires a plan. Here is how to think about yours.\n\nKNOW YOUR OPTIONS AFTER HIGH SCHOOL:\n1. Four-year university: Traditional college degree. High cost, high earning potential in many fields. Requires GPA, test scores, essays.\n2. Community college: 2-year degree or transfer pathway. Much lower cost. Underrated starting point.\n3. Trade/vocational school: Electrician, plumber, HVAC, welder, machinist. High demand. Excellent wages. Often 2 years or less.\n4. Military: Full pay, training, benefits, and GI Bill for college after service.\n5. Entrepreneurship: Start a business with skills you already have.\n6. Apprenticeship: Earn while you learn. Available in dozens of trades and tech fields.\n\nIF COLLEGE IS YOUR PATH:\n\nStart in 9th grade:\n- Maintain GPA (colleges see all four years)\n- Take challenging courses (AP, IB, dual enrollment)\n- Build extracurriculars that show leadership and commitment\n\nJunior year:\n- Take SAT/ACT — twice if needed\n- Research schools that fit your goals and finances\n- Visit campuses if possible\n\nSenior year:\n- Meet all application deadlines (early action/early decision = better chance)\n- Apply for EVERY scholarship you qualify for\n- Write strong, authentic essays — admissions is reading for the real you\n- Apply for FAFSA immediately on October 1\n\nFINANCIAL AID BASICS:\n- FAFSA: Free Application for Federal Student Aid. File every year.\n- Grants: Free money (Pell Grant for low-income students)\n- Scholarships: Free money (academic, athletic, community, identity-based)\n- Loans: Must be repaid with interest — borrow only what you truly need\n\nDO NOT TAKE ON MORE DEBT THAN YOUR EXPECTED FIRST-YEAR SALARY.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What is your plan after high school?\n- What GPA are you currently at, and what do you want it to be?\n- What scholarships could you apply for right now?',
    2, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0005-0003-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000005',
    'Setting Academic Goals',
    E'SETTING ACADEMIC GOALS\n\nYou cannot hit a target you cannot see. Academic goals give you direction, motivation, and a measure of your progress.\n\nWHY GOALS BEAT EFFORT ALONE:\nMany students try hard but stay stuck because they have no specific target. Hard work aimed at a clear goal is exponentially more effective than unfocused effort.\n\nSMART GOALS IN ACADEMICS:\nSpecific: "I will raise my math grade from a C to a B+"\nMeasurable: "I will score at least 85% on the next three tests"\nAchievable: Set stretch goals that require effort but are realistic\nRelevant: Connected to something you care about\nTime-bound: By the end of this semester\n\nTHE GOAL-HABIT CONNECTION:\nGoals tell you where to go. Habits are how you get there.\nGoal: "Raise GPA to 3.5"\nHabit: "Study for 45 minutes every day after school before doing anything else"\n\nDEAL WITH OBSTACLES IN ADVANCE:\nFor every goal, ask: "What might stop me from doing this?" Then plan how you will handle it.\nObstacle: "I get distracted at home"\nSolution: "I will study at the library every Tuesday and Thursday"\n\nTRACK YOUR PROGRESS:\nCheck in on your goals weekly. What is working? What needs to change? Adjust.\n\nGET ACCOUNTABILITY:\nTell your mentor or a trusted friend your goal. Ask them to check in with you. Accountability dramatically increases follow-through.\n\nCELEBRATE MILESTONES:\nAcknowledge progress. You do not wait until the final grade to feel good — celebrate every test you improved on, every homework streak, every late night you pushed through.\n\nDEAL WITH FAILURE WELL:\nA bad test is not the end. It is information. What did you miss? How do you study it differently? Resilience is a skill you can build.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What is one specific academic goal you want to achieve this semester?\n- What daily habit would move you toward that goal?\n- Who will you tell about this goal to create accountability?',
    3, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0005-0004-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000005',
    'Reading, Writing & Critical Thinking',
    E'READING, WRITING & CRITICAL THINKING\n\nEvery subject in school — and most challenges in life — require you to read well, write clearly, and think critically. These are foundational skills.\n\nWHY READING MATTERS:\nPeople who read regularly have larger vocabularies, better writing skills, stronger critical thinking, and broader knowledge. CEOs average 4-5 books per month. The knowledge gap between readers and non-readers grows every year.\n\nHOW TO READ BETTER:\n- Active reading: Underline, annotate, and question what you read\n- Ask: What is the main point? What evidence supports it? Do I agree?\n- Read diverse material: News, books, essays, not just social media\n- Set a daily reading habit: Even 15 minutes per day adds up to 10+ books per year\n\nWRITING IS THINKING:\nClear writing comes from clear thinking. If your essay is confusing, it is usually because your thinking is confusing. Writing forces you to organize your ideas.\n\nTHE BASICS OF A STRONG ESSAY:\n1. Clear thesis: One sentence that states your main argument\n2. Supporting paragraphs: Each paragraph makes one point and backs it up with evidence\n3. Transitions: Connect ideas smoothly\n4. Conclusion: Synthesize — do not just repeat what you said\n\nWRITING TIPS:\n- Write a rough draft first, edit second. Never try to perfect as you go.\n- Read your writing out loud — you will hear problems you cannot see\n- Get feedback from someone else before submitting\n- Short, clear sentences are better than long, complicated ones\n\nCRITICAL THINKING:\nBefore accepting information, ask:\n- Who is saying this, and what is their motivation?\n- What evidence supports this claim?\n- What are the alternative viewpoints?\n- Is this logical, or does it just feel true?\n\nIn an age of misinformation, critical thinking is one of the most valuable skills you can possess.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- When was the last time you read a book by choice?\n- What is one piece of writing (essay, paper, email) you need to improve?\n- What is one news story or claim you have recently questioned?',
    4, 20, NOW()
  ),


-- =============================================
-- TRACK 6: IDENTITY & CHARACTER
-- =============================================

  (
    '44444444-0006-0001-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000006',
    'Who Are You? Defining Your Identity',
    E'WHO ARE YOU? DEFINING YOUR IDENTITY\n\nIf you do not define yourself, the world will define you — and it will not be kind or accurate.\n\nTHE IDENTITY QUESTION:\nMost people go through life reacting to what others think of them. They build their identity from the outside in — based on social media likes, what their friends think, what their neighborhood says is cool.\n\nStrong men build their identity from the inside out — rooted in their own values, beliefs, and convictions.\n\nWHAT MAKES UP YOUR IDENTITY:\n- Your values: What you believe is right and important\n- Your character: How you behave when no one is watching\n- Your story: Where you came from and what you have been through\n- Your purpose: What you are here to do and become\n- Your roles: Son, brother, student, athlete, friend — but none of these fully define you\n\nTHE INFLUENCE AUDIT:\nFor one week, pay attention to where your ideas about yourself come from:\n- What do your closest friends believe about you?\n- What does social media reinforce about who you should be?\n- What does your family expect?\n- What do YOU believe about yourself?\n\nAre these sources building you up or tearing you down?\n\nYOUR STORY IS NOT YOUR DESTINY:\nMany powerful men came from broken homes, poverty, abuse, and trauma. Your past informs you. It does not define you. You are not your circumstances. You are your choices.\n\nBUILDING A SELF-IMAGE WORTH DEFENDING:\nWrite down ten things you believe about yourself — positive and true. Read them regularly. What we repeatedly tell ourselves becomes what we believe.\n\nCHARACTER IS WHO YOU ARE UNDER PRESSURE:\nAnyone can have good values on a good day. Character shows up when things are hard, when no one is watching, and when the cost of integrity is high.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- How do you currently describe yourself to others?\n- What five words would you want people to use to describe your character?\n- Where do you feel pressure to be someone you are not?',
    1, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0006-0002-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000006',
    'Values, Integrity & Being Your Word',
    E'VALUES, INTEGRITY & BEING YOUR WORD\n\nYour word is the most valuable currency you have. Guard it carefully.\n\nWHAT ARE VALUES?\nValues are the principles you are not willing to compromise. They are not what you say you believe — they are what you consistently choose when it costs you something.\n\nCOMMON VALUES TO CONSIDER:\nHonesty, loyalty, courage, discipline, compassion, justice, faith, service, family, excellence, respect, accountability\n\nKnowing your values gives you a compass for hard decisions. When two paths are in front of you and you do not know which to choose, ask: which choice aligns with who I want to be?\n\nINTEGRITY:\nIntegrity means your inner and outer worlds match — what you believe and what you do are the same thing. A man of integrity:\n- Does what he says he will do\n- Tells the truth even when it is uncomfortable\n- Behaves the same way whether he is being watched or not\n- Takes responsibility for his mistakes without making excuses\n\nBEING YOUR WORD:\nIn many communities, your word is your bond. If you say you will be somewhere, be there. If you commit to something, follow through. Consistent follow-through builds a reputation that opens doors. Broken commitments close them.\n\nWHEN YOU FALL SHORT:\nNo one has perfect integrity. You will make mistakes. The measure of your character is not perfection — it is what you do after you fail. Do you own it, learn from it, and do better? Or do you blame others and repeat the pattern?\n\nCOURAGE AND INTEGRITY:\nSometimes integrity requires courage — to tell a hard truth, to stand against a crowd, to do the right thing when everyone else is going wrong. This is one of the hardest things a person can do, and one of the most defining.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What are your top five personal values?\n- Describe a time when you had to choose between the easy path and the right path. What did you choose?\n- Is there an area of your life where your actions do not match your values?',
    2, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0006-0003-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000006',
    'Navigating Peer Pressure',
    E'NAVIGATING PEER PRESSURE\n\nEveryone faces pressure to go along with the crowd. Your ability to resist the wrong crowd — and find the right one — will shape your entire future.\n\nWHY PEER PRESSURE IS SO POWERFUL:\nHumans are wired for social belonging. The fear of rejection or exclusion activates the same part of the brain as physical pain. This is not weakness — it is biology. Understanding it gives you power over it.\n\nTYPES OF PEER PRESSURE:\n- Direct: Someone explicitly pressures you to do something ("Come on, just do it")\n- Indirect: You feel pulled toward a behavior because everyone around you is doing it\n- Self-imposed: You pressure yourself to fit in without anyone asking\n\nTHE CIRCLE OF INFLUENCE:\nLook at your five closest friends. You are likely to become a blend of those five people — their habits, their values, their trajectories.\n\nThis is not about judging others. It is about being intentional about who you allow to influence you.\n\nHOW TO HANDLE DIRECT PRESSURE:\n- You do not owe anyone an explanation. "No thanks" is a complete sentence.\n- If someone keeps pushing after a clear no, that is a person who does not respect you.\n- Practice your response before you need it. Role-play the scenario with your mentor.\n- Blame your values, not your fear: "That''s not who I am."\n\nFINDING YOUR PEOPLE:\nThe solution to a bad circle is not isolation — it is finding a better circle. Look for people involved in things you care about: sports teams, church, community organizations, clubs, mentorship programs. Your people exist. You have to go find them.\n\nBEING A POSITIVE INFLUENCE:\nAs you grow, you will become a peer influencer yourself. Use that power intentionally. The young man behind you is watching what you do.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- Is there a situation in your life where you feel pressure to act against your values?\n- Who in your circle has a positive influence on you? Who has a negative influence?\n- What can you say next time someone pressures you into something you do not want to do?',
    3, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0006-0004-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000006',
    'Growing Into Manhood',
    E'GROWING INTO MANHOOD\n\nBeing a man is not about age, size, or what you can take. It is about what you can give, endure, and protect.\n\nWHAT IS A MAN?\nOur culture sends confusing messages about manhood. Some say a man is someone who shows no weakness. Some say a man is measured by what he owns, who he sleeps with, or how hard he is.\n\nNone of that is true manhood.\n\nReal manhood is:\n- Taking responsibility for your actions and your life\n- Protecting and providing for those who depend on you\n- Living with integrity, even when it costs you\n- Controlling your emotions rather than being controlled by them\n- Building something worth leaving behind\n- Being present — as a son, friend, partner, and eventually a father\n\nTHE RITES OF PASSAGE:\nHistorically, every culture had rituals marking the transition from boy to man — trials that required something from the young man. Today, many of those rituals are gone. Programs like Iron Sharpens Iron exist to fill that gap intentionally.\n\nBOYS DO WHAT IS EASY. MEN DO WHAT IS NECESSARY.\nThis is not about being hard — it is about being responsible. A boy avoids discomfort. A man walks toward necessary hard things: difficult conversations, taking on responsibility, admitting when he is wrong.\n\nTHE FATHER WOUND:\nMany young men carry a wound from an absent, abusive, or emotionally unavailable father. This wound is real. It affects your relationships, your sense of worth, and your idea of what a man is.\n\nYou can be healed from this wound. And you can refuse to pass it to the next generation.\n\nYOUR LEGACY STARTS NOW:\nEvery day you are building a reputation, a character, and a pattern of behavior. You are practicing the kind of man you will be at 30, 40, and 50.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What does manhood mean to you right now?\n- Who is a man you respect and want to model your life after? What is it about him?\n- What is one area where you need to grow from boy to man thinking?',
    4, 20, NOW()
  ),


-- =============================================
-- TRACK 7: COMMUNICATION & LEADERSHIP
-- =============================================

  (
    '44444444-0007-0001-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000007',
    'The Power of Your Voice',
    E'THE POWER OF YOUR VOICE\n\nHow you communicate shapes every relationship, opportunity, and outcome in your life. Your voice is one of your most powerful tools.\n\nCOMMUNICATION IS MORE THAN WORDS:\nResearch suggests that communication is:\n- 7% the actual words you say\n- 38% tone and voice\n- 55% body language\n\nYou can say the right words with the wrong tone and still damage a relationship. Learn to align what you say with how you say it.\n\nSPEAKING WITH CLARITY:\n- Know your point before you start speaking\n- Use simple, direct language — complexity is not intelligence\n- Get to the point. Do not bury your main message.\n- Pause before you speak, especially when emotional\n\nBODY LANGUAGE BASICS:\n- Eye contact: Shows confidence and respect\n- Posture: Stand/sit up straight — it projects confidence and affects how you feel\n- Handshake: Firm, not crushing. Always in greeting and parting.\n- Facial expressions: Your face tells people how to interpret your words\n\nTONE IN DIFFERENT CONTEXTS:\nYou need multiple communication styles:\n- Peer conversation (casual, relaxed)\n- Professional conversation (formal, clear, respectful)\n- Conflict conversation (calm, controlled, clear)\n- Public speaking (confident, engaging, prepared)\n\nSwitching between these appropriately is called code-switching. It is not fake — it is intelligent communication.\n\nPUBLIC SPEAKING:\nMost people fear public speaking more than death. Build this skill early and it will set you apart your entire life.\n\nStart small: Raise your hand in class. Speak up in small group settings. Practice presentations before you give them.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- How would you rate your communication skills on a scale of 1-10?\n- What is the hardest communication situation for you (conflict, public speaking, authority figures)?\n- What is one habit you can build to communicate more effectively?',
    1, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0007-0002-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000007',
    'Active Listening & Emotional Intelligence',
    E'ACTIVE LISTENING & EMOTIONAL INTELLIGENCE\n\nThe most powerful communicators are not the best talkers. They are the best listeners.\n\nWHY LISTENING IS RARE AND VALUABLE:\nMost people listen to respond, not to understand. While someone is talking, they are preparing their rebuttal. Real listening is rare — and when you do it well, people feel heard in a way that builds deep trust.\n\nACTIVE LISTENING SKILLS:\n1. Give your full attention — phone down, eye contact up\n2. Do not interrupt\n3. Reflect back: "So what I''m hearing is..."\n4. Ask clarifying questions, not leading questions\n5. Validate the feeling before jumping to solutions: "That sounds really frustrating."\n\nEMOTIONAL INTELLIGENCE (EQ):\nEQ is your ability to identify and manage your own emotions, and to understand and influence the emotions of others. Research shows EQ is a stronger predictor of life success than IQ.\n\nTHE FOUR COMPONENTS OF EQ:\n1. Self-awareness: Knowing what you are feeling and why\n2. Self-management: Regulating your emotions and impulses\n3. Social awareness: Reading others'' emotions accurately\n4. Relationship management: Using emotional awareness to guide interactions\n\nPRACTICING EQ:\n- Name your emotions specifically (not just "mad" — "frustrated," "disrespected," "embarrassed")\n- Pause before reacting in emotional situations\n- Try to understand what the other person is feeling before responding\n- Manage your stress before entering important conversations\n\nEMPATHY IS STRENGTH:\nEmpathy — the ability to understand someone else''s perspective — is not soft. It is strategic. Leaders with high empathy build more loyal teams, resolve conflict faster, and make better decisions.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- Think of someone in your life who makes you feel truly heard. What do they do that creates that feeling?\n- In your last conflict, what was the other person actually feeling?\n- What emotion do you find hardest to manage, and why?',
    2, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0007-0003-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000007',
    'Conflict Resolution Without Violence',
    E'CONFLICT RESOLUTION WITHOUT VIOLENCE\n\nConflict is inevitable. Violence is a choice. Learning to resolve conflict without it is one of the most important skills a young man can build.\n\nWHY CONFLICT HAPPENS:\nConflict is a normal part of life. It arises from competing needs, misunderstandings, hurt feelings, and differences in values. It is not inherently bad — it is how you handle it that matters.\n\nWHAT MAKES CONFLICTS ESCALATE:\n- Responding with aggression when you feel disrespected\n- Saying things you cannot take back when emotional\n- Bringing an audience into the situation (social pressure to "not back down")\n- Pride that makes de-escalation feel like weakness\n- Jumping to conclusions without hearing the full story\n\nDE-ESCALATION TECHNIQUES:\n1. Lower your voice — people naturally mirror your tone\n2. Create physical space — step back physically to reduce tension\n3. Delay when emotional — "Let me think about this and get back to you"\n4. Agree on the goal — "We both want this to be resolved, right?"\n5. Separate the person from the problem — attack the issue, not the individual\n\nTHE CONFLICT RESOLUTION FRAMEWORK:\n1. Listen first — fully hear the other person''s perspective\n2. Acknowledge their feelings — even if you disagree with their actions\n3. State your perspective using "I" statements — "I felt disrespected when..."\n4. Find common ground — what do you both want?\n5. Agree on a solution — be specific about what changes\n6. Follow through — do what you agreed to\n\nWHEN TO WALK AWAY:\nNot every conflict is worth engaging. If the situation is dangerous, if the other person is not interested in resolution, or if you are too emotional to think clearly — walking away is the smart, strategic choice. It is not weakness.\n\nVIOLENCE HAS A LONG COST:\nA few seconds of violence can result in criminal charges, injury, expulsion, or death. Nothing is worth that price.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- How do you currently handle conflict? Does it tend to escalate or resolve?\n- What triggers make it hard for you to think clearly in conflict?\n- Think of an unresolved conflict in your life. What would resolution look like?',
    3, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0007-0004-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000007',
    'Leading Before You Have a Title',
    E'LEADING BEFORE YOU HAVE A TITLE\n\nLeadership is not a position. It is a way of showing up. And you can start right now.\n\nWHAT LEADERSHIP ACTUALLY IS:\nLeadership is influence. Every person has influence over someone — a younger sibling, a classmate, someone watching what you do. The question is: what are you doing with it?\n\nYOU ARE ALREADY A LEADER IF:\n- Younger kids look up to you\n- Your friends ask for your opinion\n- You set the tone in a room you walk into\n- Others follow your lead (positively or negatively)\n\nTYPES OF LEADERSHIP:\n- Servant leadership: Leading by serving others first. The strongest and most sustainable form.\n- Positional leadership: Leading because of a title or role (captain, president, manager)\n- Relational leadership: Leading through the trust you have built\n\nThe most respected leaders combine all three.\n\nSERVANT LEADERSHIP IN ACTION:\n- You do the unglamorous work without being asked\n- You give credit to others, take responsibility for failures\n- You invest in the people around you\n- You speak up when something is wrong, even when it is uncomfortable\n\nCOMMON LEADERSHIP MISTAKES:\n- Trying to be liked instead of respected\n- Making decisions to benefit yourself at the group''s expense\n- Leading with fear or intimidation instead of inspiration\n- Refusing to listen to feedback\n\nLEADERSHIP UNDER PRESSURE:\nAnyone can lead when things are going well. Real leadership shows up when things are hard — when the team is losing, when morale is low, when the right path is unpopular. How you behave in those moments is your true leadership test.\n\nPRACTICE LEADERSHIP NOW:\n- Volunteer for things others avoid\n- Be the one who calms things down, not escalates\n- Be on time and reliable — every time\n- Include people who are left out\n\nREFLECTION:\n- In what area of your life are you already a leader?\n- Who has been influenced by your example — positively or negatively?\n- What kind of leader do you want to be known as?',
    4, 20, NOW()
  ),


-- =============================================
-- TRACK 8: CAREER READINESS
-- =============================================

  (
    '44444444-0008-0001-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000008',
    'Discovering Your Career Path',
    E'DISCOVERING YOUR CAREER PATH\n\nYou do not need to have your career figured out at 16. But you do need to start asking the right questions.\n\nTHE CAREER DISCOVERY PROCESS:\nCareer clarity rarely arrives fully formed. It emerges through exploration, experience, and honest self-reflection.\n\nTHREE CAREER DISCOVERY QUESTIONS:\n1. What am I good at? (Skills and talents)\n2. What do I enjoy? (Passion and interests)\n3. What does the world need and pay for? (Market demand)\n\nThe intersection of all three is your career sweet spot.\n\nTYPES OF CAREERS TO EXPLORE:\n- Technology: Software development, cybersecurity, data science, IT\n- Trades: Electrician, plumber, HVAC, welder (high demand, excellent wages)\n- Healthcare: Nursing, physical therapy, medical technology\n- Business: Finance, management, marketing, entrepreneurship\n- Creative: Design, media, writing, music\n- Public Service: Law enforcement, military, social work, government\n- Education: Teaching, coaching, mentoring\n\nHOW TO EXPLORE CAREERS:\n- Shadow someone in a field that interests you\n- Get a part-time job or internship\n- Interview professionals in careers you are curious about\n- Take electives and elective courses that align with your interests\n- Look at the Bureau of Labor Statistics Occupational Outlook Handbook (free online)\n\nGROWTH FIELDS (HIGH DEMAND THROUGH 2035):\n- Technology and cybersecurity\n- Healthcare and eldercare\n- Skilled trades (major shortage)\n- Renewable energy\n- Mental health services\n\nINCOME MATTERS:\nPursuit of passion without regard to income can create financial hardship. Conversely, pursuing only income without any passion leads to misery. Find the overlap.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What activities make you lose track of time?\n- What do people regularly compliment you on or ask you for help with?\n- What is one career you want to research or shadow in the next 90 days?',
    1, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0008-0002-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000008',
    'Resume, References & First Impressions',
    E'RESUME, REFERENCES & FIRST IMPRESSIONS\n\nYou often have 30 seconds to make a first impression. Make it count.\n\nYOUR FIRST RESUME:\nEven if you have never had a job, you have experience worth listing. Start collecting it now.\n\nWHAT TO INCLUDE (EVEN WITH NO WORK HISTORY):\n- Contact information (professional email address — firstname.lastname@email.com)\n- Education (school, expected graduation year, GPA if above 3.0)\n- Skills (software, languages, certifications)\n- Volunteer work and community service\n- Extracurricular activities and leadership roles\n- Awards and recognitions\n- Any personal projects, businesses, or creative work\n\nRESUME RULES:\n- One page for entry-level positions\n- Use bullet points, not paragraphs\n- Start each bullet with an action verb (Led, Created, Managed, Increased, Built)\n- Tailor your resume for each job — use keywords from the job description\n- Proofread three times. Have someone else proofread it too.\n- Save as a PDF\n\nYOUR PROFESSIONAL EMAIL:\nIf your email is something like "drip_king2007@hotmail.com" — create a new one today. First impressions start before the interview.\n\nREFERENCES:\nA reference is someone who will vouch for your character and abilities to an employer. Good references include:\n- Teachers, coaches, youth pastors, or mentors\n- Previous employers or clients\n- Community leaders\n\nAlways ask permission before listing someone as a reference. Brief them on the job you are applying for.\n\nFIRST IMPRESSIONS IN PERSON:\n- Arrive 5-10 minutes early\n- Dress one level above the job dress code\n- Firm handshake, eye contact, genuine smile\n- Phone away and silenced\n- Know the name of who you are meeting and use it\n\nREFLECTION:\n- Have you built your resume yet? If not, what would be on it?\n- Who would you list as a reference?\n- What first impression do you currently make? How do you know?',
    2, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0008-0003-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000008',
    'Nailing the Interview',
    E'NAILING THE INTERVIEW\n\nThe interview is not a test of what you know. It is a test of who you are and whether you are the right fit. Prepare accordingly.\n\nBEFORE THE INTERVIEW:\n- Research the company or organization. Know what they do, their mission, recent news.\n- Re-read the job description. Know exactly what skills they are looking for.\n- Prepare answers to common questions (practice out loud, not just in your head)\n- Prepare 2-3 questions to ask them (shows genuine interest)\n- Plan your outfit the night before\n- Know the exact location and how to get there\n\nCOMMON INTERVIEW QUESTIONS:\n- "Tell me about yourself." (90-second professional summary, not your life story)\n- "Why do you want this job?"\n- "What are your strengths?"\n- "What is a weakness?" (name a real one + how you are working on it)\n- "Tell me about a time you handled a difficult situation."\n- "Where do you see yourself in 5 years?"\n\nTHE STAR METHOD (for behavioral questions):\nSituation: Set the context\nTask: What was your responsibility?\nAction: What specific steps did you take?\nResult: What happened? (Quantify if possible)\n\nDURING THE INTERVIEW:\n- Slow down — nervous people talk fast\n- It is okay to pause and think before answering\n- Be honest — interviewers can tell when you are performing vs. being real\n- Show enthusiasm — most interviewers hire enthusiasm over credentials for entry-level\n\nAFTER THE INTERVIEW:\n- Send a thank-you email within 24 hours (brief, sincere, restate your interest)\n- Follow up once if you have not heard back in the stated timeframe\n- Whether you get the job or not, ask for feedback — it makes you better\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What questions do you feel most unprepared to answer in an interview?\n- Practice your "tell me about yourself" answer out loud right now. How did it sound?\n- What is one way you can stand out from other candidates?',
    3, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0008-0004-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000008',
    'Workplace Culture & Professionalism',
    E'WORKPLACE CULTURE & PROFESSIONALISM\n\nGetting the job is step one. Keeping it, thriving in it, and building from it requires professional skills that most people learn the hard way.\n\nWHAT PROFESSIONALISM MEANS:\nProfessionalism is the collection of behaviors, attitudes, and habits that make you reliable, trustworthy, and effective in a work environment.\n\nPROFESSIONAL HABITS:\n- Punctuality: Be on time, every time. If something comes up, communicate early.\n- Follow through: Do what you say you will do. If you cannot, let someone know before the deadline.\n- Dress appropriately: Understand the dress code and lean toward the more professional end.\n- Language: Watch your language in professional settings — what is fine with friends is not always fine at work.\n- Phone etiquette: No personal phone use during work time. Step away for calls.\n\nWORKPLACE RELATIONSHIPS:\n- Respect everyone regardless of their position — especially support staff\n- Avoid gossip and drama — it always comes back to you\n- Disagree professionally: "I see it differently, and here is why..."\n- Take feedback well — do not get defensive when corrected\n- Be the coworker you would want to work with\n\nUNDERSTANDING WORKPLACE CULTURE:\nEvery organization has an unwritten culture — how decisions are made, how people are expected to act, what is rewarded. Observe before you act. Ask questions. Find a mentor inside the organization.\n\nGROWTH MINDSET AT WORK:\n- Volunteer for projects beyond your job description\n- Ask your manager: "What would exceptional look like in this role?"\n- Seek feedback regularly — do not wait for performance reviews\n- Be the one who solves problems rather than creates them\n\nKNOW YOUR RIGHTS:\n- You have the right to a safe workplace\n- Discrimination based on race, religion, gender, or disability is illegal\n- If you experience harassment, document it and report it through proper channels\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What professional habit do you most need to develop?\n- How do you currently respond when someone gives you constructive criticism?\n- What kind of employee do you want to be known as?',
    4, 20, NOW()
  ),


-- =============================================
-- TRACK 9: RELATIONSHIPS & RESPECT
-- =============================================

  (
    '44444444-0009-0001-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000009',
    'Family: Your Foundation',
    E'FAMILY: YOUR FOUNDATION\n\nFamily is complicated. But understanding your family dynamics — and your role in them — is foundational to who you become.\n\nWHAT FAMILY TEACHES YOU:\nWhether you grew up in a stable home or a chaotic one, your family was your first school. It taught you (consciously or unconsciously):\n- How conflict is handled\n- Whether you are valued and loved\n- What relationships look like\n- How money is managed\n- What men are supposed to be\n\nSome of those lessons were healthy. Some were not. The work of becoming a man includes deciding which lessons to keep and which to unlearn.\n\nHONORING YOUR PARENTS:\nThis does not mean agreeing with everything they do or did. It means respecting the sacrifice, even when it was imperfect. Many parents did the best they could with the tools they had.\n\nIf your parents were absent, abusive, or hurtful — you are allowed to grieve that. You are also responsible for not letting their failure define your future.\n\nSIBLING DYNAMICS:\nIf you are an older sibling, younger eyes are watching you constantly. What you model matters.\nIf you are a younger sibling, you have an opportunity to learn from both the good and bad examples in front of you.\n\nEXTENDED FAMILY AND COMMUNITY:\nIn many cultures, uncles, grandparents, cousins, and community elders are part of the family network. These relationships carry wisdom, history, and identity. Invest in them.\n\nCOMING FROM A BROKEN HOME:\nMillions of young men grew up without a father present. This wound is real and significant. But it is not disqualifying. Some of history''s greatest men rose from broken homes and decided to stop the cycle.\n\nYou can be the one who does it differently.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What is the most important thing your family taught you (good or bad)?\n- Is there a family relationship that needs healing or attention?\n- What family tradition or value do you want to carry forward in your own life?',
    1, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0009-0002-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000009',
    'Friendship: Who Is in Your Circle',
    E'FRIENDSHIP: WHO IS IN YOUR CIRCLE\n\nYou become who you surround yourself with. Choose carefully.\n\nWHY FRIENDSHIPS MATTER MORE THAN YOU THINK:\nYour closest friends shape your language, habits, beliefs, and trajectory. Research shows that your income will be near the average of your five closest friends. Your habits, health behaviors, and values are also heavily influenced by your peer group.\n\nTHIS IS NOT ABOUT JUDGING OTHERS:\nIt is about being intentional. You can care about people without giving them unlimited access to your inner circle.\n\nLEVELS OF FRIENDSHIP:\n- Acquaintances: People you know. Many. Low investment.\n- Casual friends: People you enjoy spending time with. Some investment.\n- Close friends: People you trust with real things. Few. High investment.\n- Inner circle: The 1-3 people you are accountable to and vulnerable with. Very few.\n\nWHAT TO LOOK FOR IN A REAL FRIEND:\n- Tells you the truth, even when it is uncomfortable\n- Celebrates your wins without jealousy\n- Is there when things are hard, not just when things are good\n- Has values you respect\n- Makes you better, not worse\n\nWARNING SIGNS IN FRIENDSHIPS:\n- Constant drama or chaos follows them everywhere\n- They pull you toward things that go against your values\n- They are only around when they need something\n- They put you down, even "jokingly"\n- They are jealous of your progress\n\nBEING A GOOD FRIEND:\n- Be reliable: Show up when you say you will\n- Listen well: Be the friend who actually hears people\n- Be honest: Kindly, but honestly\n- Celebrate others: Genuine joy for your friend''s success is a mark of character\n\nLONELINESS IS REAL:\nMany young men feel lonely even when surrounded by people. If this is you, it may mean you are missing authentic connection, not just company. Vulnerability with the right people is the cure.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- Who are the three people who have the most influence on your decisions right now?\n- What kind of friend are you?\n- Is there a friendship that is holding you back that you need to distance yourself from?',
    2, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0009-0003-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000009',
    'Romantic Relationships & Integrity',
    E'ROMANTIC RELATIONSHIPS & INTEGRITY\n\nHow you treat women is one of the clearest measurements of your character. Do not fail this test.\n\nWHAT CULTURE SAYS vs. WHAT IS TRUE:\nCulture (music, movies, social media) teaches young men that women are conquests, that vulnerability is weakness, and that sex without commitment is the goal.\n\nThis is a lie that produces broken men, broken women, and broken families.\n\nFOUNDATIONS OF HEALTHY RELATIONSHIPS:\n- Mutual respect: Both people''s feelings, boundaries, and goals matter equally\n- Honesty: No manipulation, no games, no pretending to be someone you are not\n- Emotional maturity: Both people can manage their emotions\n- Shared values: Not identical — but compatible\n- Independence: Two whole people coming together, not two broken people filling each other''s gaps\n\nYOU ARE NOT READY FOR A RELATIONSHIP IF:\n- You cannot manage your own emotions\n- You are looking for a relationship to fix your loneliness or pain\n- You do not have your own life direction\n- You do not respect the other person''s "no"\n\nCONSENT IS NOT COMPLICATED:\nAffirmative, enthusiastic, ongoing agreement. Anything less is not consent. This is both morally right and legally required.\n\nEMOTIONAL MANIPULATION IS ABUSE:\nControlling, isolating, belittling, or threatening someone emotionally is abusive — even without physical violence. Do not do it. Do not accept it.\n\nBREAKUPS WITH INTEGRITY:\n- Be honest, not cruel\n- Do not ghost — it is cowardly\n- Take responsibility for your part in what did not work\n\nINVESTING IN YOUR FUTURE FAMILY NOW:\nThe man you are becoming right now is the husband and father you will be. The habits, the temper, the integrity, the discipline — all of it carries forward.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What does a healthy relationship look like based on what you''ve seen in your life?\n- What is one thing you want to work on before entering a serious relationship?\n- How do you want to be described by someone who was in a relationship with you?',
    3, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0009-0004-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000009',
    'Setting Boundaries & Respecting Others',
    E'SETTING BOUNDARIES & RESPECTING OTHERS\n\nBoundaries protect relationships, not just individuals. Learning to set and respect them is a sign of emotional maturity.\n\nWHAT ARE BOUNDARIES?\nBoundaries are the limits you set for how others can treat you and what you are willing to do. They are not walls to keep people out — they are guidelines that make healthy relationships possible.\n\nWHY BOUNDARIES MATTER:\n- They protect your mental and emotional health\n- They communicate respect for yourself\n- They create clarity in relationships\n- They prevent resentment from building\n\nTYPES OF BOUNDARIES:\n- Physical: Your personal space and body\n- Emotional: What topics you share, with whom, and when\n- Time: How you choose to spend your time\n- Digital: Privacy on your devices and social accounts\n- Relationship: What behaviors you will and will not accept from others\n\nHOW TO SET A BOUNDARY:\n1. Identify what you need or do not want\n2. Communicate it clearly and directly: "I''m not comfortable with that."\n3. Be consistent — enforce it even when it is uncomfortable\n4. Do not over-explain or apologize for having needs\n\nRESPECTING OTHERS'' BOUNDARIES:\n- When someone says no, stop — immediately and completely\n- Do not take it personally when someone has a limit you do not understand\n- Ask before assuming (especially in physical contact)\n- Pay attention to nonverbal cues — discomfort does not always come with words\n\nBOUNDARIES ARE NOT REJECTION:\nWhen someone sets a boundary with you, it does not mean they do not like or trust you. It means they are being honest about their needs. Honor that.\n\nSELF-RESPECT AND BOUNDARIES:\nYou cannot set boundaries if you do not believe your needs are valid. Building self-respect is the foundation of setting healthy limits.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What is a boundary you need to set in a current relationship?\n- Have you ever crossed someone else''s boundary without realizing it? What happened?\n- What would it look like to respect yourself more in one area of your life?',
    4, 20, NOW()
  ),


-- =============================================
-- TRACK 10: DIGITAL CITIZENSHIP
-- =============================================

  (
    '44444444-0010-0001-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000010',
    'Your Online Reputation',
    E'YOUR ONLINE REPUTATION\n\nYour digital footprint is permanent, searchable, and already being reviewed by people who will impact your future.\n\nTHE DIGITAL PERMANENT RECORD:\nSchools, employers, colleges, and law enforcement all search social media. What you post at 15 can be seen by a college admissions officer at 17, an employer at 21, or in a courtroom at 19.\n\nSCREENSHOTS ARE FOREVER:\nOnce something is posted, shared, or even privately sent, assume it can and will be seen by anyone. The Snapchat "disappears" — the screenshot does not.\n\nGOOGLE YOURSELF:\nSearch your own name right now. What comes up? Is it the story you want to tell? If not, start building a better one.\n\nTHREE QUESTIONS BEFORE YOU POST:\n1. Would I be comfortable if my mom, a college admissions officer, and a potential employer all saw this?\n2. Could this be misunderstood out of context?\n3. Does this represent who I am and who I want to be?\n\nNEGATIVE CONTENT TO AVOID:\n- Violence, weapons, or threats\n- Illegal activity (drugs, alcohol underage, vandalism)\n- Explicit sexual content\n- Bullying, harassment, or offensive language\n- Disrespecting authority figures, schools, or employers (even past ones)\n\nDELETE IT BEFORE IT FOLLOWS YOU:\nDo an audit of your social media profiles. Delete anything you would not want an employer or admissions officer to see. This is housekeeping every serious young man should do.\n\nCONTROLLING YOUR NARRATIVE:\nThe best way to manage your online reputation is to actively build a positive one. Post about your accomplishments, your interests, your community work, your growth. Flood out the bad with the good.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- If an employer looked at your social media today, what would they think?\n- Is there anything you have posted that you regret or should delete?\n- What positive things could you post that accurately represent who you are?',
    1, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0010-0002-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000010',
    'Social Media: Power & Danger',
    E'SOCIAL MEDIA: POWER & DANGER\n\nSocial media is not going away. The question is whether it is using you, or you are using it.\n\nTHE BUSINESS MODEL OF SOCIAL MEDIA:\nEvery platform — Instagram, TikTok, Snapchat, YouTube — is designed to maximize the time you spend on it. They use psychological triggers (variable rewards, social validation, fear of missing out) to keep you scrolling.\n\nYou are not the customer. You are the product. Advertisers pay for your attention.\n\nTHE REAL COSTS OF EXCESSIVE USE:\n- Time: Average teen spends 7+ hours per day on screens. That is 2,555 hours per year — time that could become a skill, a business, or a relationship.\n- Mental health: Heavy social media use is correlated with increased anxiety, depression, and loneliness, especially in young men.\n- Comparison: You are comparing your real life to everyone else''s highlight reel. This comparison is always unfair to you.\n- Focus: Constant notifications fragment your attention and make deep focus — necessary for achievement — harder.\n\nSIGNS YOU ARE BEING USED:\n- You reach for your phone as soon as you wake up\n- You feel worse after scrolling, not better\n- You check likes/views anxiously after posting\n- You feel anxious without your phone\n\nTAKING BACK CONTROL:\n- Set screen time limits in your phone settings\n- Remove social media apps from your home screen\n- Designate phone-free times (meals, first hour of morning, last hour before sleep)\n- Curate your feed ruthlessly — unfollow anything that makes you feel worse\n- Use social media for creation, not just consumption\n\nTURN IT INTO A TOOL:\nYouTube has tutorials that can teach you any skill. Social media can build a business. LinkedIn can open career doors. The same tools that can waste your life can accelerate it — the difference is intention.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- How many hours per day are you currently on screens?\n- How do you typically feel after a long scrolling session?\n- What could you do with the time if you cut your social media use in half?',
    2, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0010-0003-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000010',
    'Online Safety & Privacy',
    E'ONLINE SAFETY & PRIVACY\n\nThe internet contains real predators, real scams, and real dangers. Know how to protect yourself.\n\nCYBERSECURITY BASICS:\nYour personal information has monetary value to criminals. Protect it.\n\n- Passwords: Use a unique, strong password for every important account. A password manager (like Bitwarden or 1Password) helps. Never reuse passwords.\n- Two-factor authentication (2FA): Turn this on for every account that offers it. It requires a second verification even if someone steals your password.\n- Phishing: Fake emails, texts, and links designed to steal your information. Never click links in unexpected messages. Go directly to the website.\n- Public Wi-Fi: Never access banking or sensitive accounts on public Wi-Fi without a VPN.\n\nSOCIAL ENGINEERING:\nMost hacks target people, not technology. Criminals trick people into giving up information by pretending to be someone trustworthy (a bank, a tech company, a school, a love interest).\n\nRed flags: Urgent requests, requests for passwords or money, too-good-to-be-true offers.\n\nONLINE PREDATORS:\nAdults who seek to exploit minors online are a real threat. They operate on gaming platforms, social media, and messaging apps.\n\nWarning signs:\n- An adult trying to befriend you privately online\n- Someone asking for photos, especially private ones\n- Someone offering gifts, money, or opportunities in exchange for communication\n- Someone trying to isolate you from your friends and family\n\nIf this happens: Do not engage, do not send anything, tell a trusted adult immediately.\n\nSEXTING AND IMAGE-BASED ABUSE:\n- Once an image is sent, you have zero control over it\n- In many states, sending or receiving explicit images of minors is a crime — even for teens\n- Sextortion (being blackmailed with images) is a growing problem targeting young men\n\nYOUR DATA IS VALUABLE:\nApps collect enormous amounts of data about you. Read privacy settings. Limit what you share. Think before you give an app access to your location, contacts, or camera.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- Do you use strong, unique passwords for your important accounts?\n- What would you do if someone online made you feel uncomfortable?\n- What permissions have you given apps that you should review?',
    3, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0010-0004-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000010',
    'Building a Positive Personal Brand Online',
    E'BUILDING A POSITIVE PERSONAL BRAND ONLINE\n\nThe internet is the most powerful platform in human history. Use it to build your future.\n\nWHAT IS A PERSONAL BRAND?\nYour personal brand is the reputation you build online — the impression people get when they search your name, follow your accounts, or see your content.\n\nIn the modern economy, a strong personal brand can open doors that resumes cannot.\n\nPLATFORMS AND THEIR PURPOSE:\n- LinkedIn: Professional network. Start building this early. Connects you with employers, mentors, and opportunities.\n- Instagram: Visual storytelling. Show your work, your interests, your process.\n- TikTok/YouTube: Video content. Best for demonstrating skills, teaching, and building an audience.\n- Twitter/X: Thoughts, ideas, industry conversations.\n- Personal website/portfolio: The home base. Everything links back here.\n\nCONTENT THAT BUILDS YOUR BRAND:\n- Document your work and projects\n- Share what you are learning\n- Highlight your community involvement\n- Give value — teach something useful\n- Be authentic — your real story is your differentiator\n\nTHE CONSISTENCY PRINCIPLE:\nOne post does not build a brand. A hundred posts over time does. Show up consistently, even if your audience is small at first.\n\nCOLLABORATE:\nTag relevant people, join conversations, connect with others in your field of interest. Building relationships online can lead to real-world opportunities.\n\nMONETIZING A PERSONAL BRAND:\nOnce you build an audience and a reputation, opportunities emerge:\n- Sponsorships and partnerships\n- Consulting or speaking\n- Selling products or services\n- Career offers that come to you instead of you chasing them\n\nSTART NOW:\nEvery young man who builds their brand deliberately while peers are not thinking about it gains a significant head start.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What are three things you are knowledgeable or passionate about that could attract an audience?\n- What platform fits best with how you like to express yourself?\n- What is one piece of content you could create this week that represents who you are?',
    4, 20, NOW()
  ),


-- =============================================
-- TRACK 11: COMMUNITY & SERVICE
-- =============================================

  (
    '44444444-0011-0001-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000011',
    'Why Service Matters',
    E'WHY SERVICE MATTERS\n\nThe most fulfilled people in the world are not those who accumulated the most — they are those who gave the most.\n\nTHE PARADOX OF SERVICE:\nThe more you give, the more you gain — in perspective, character, relationships, and even opportunity. Service breaks you out of your own problems by connecting you to something larger than yourself.\n\nWHAT SERVICE DOES FOR YOU:\n- Builds empathy and perspective\n- Develops leadership skills in real-world contexts\n- Creates connections with adults and mentors who open doors\n- Strengthens community bonds\n- Provides a sense of purpose and meaning\n- Looks exceptional on college applications and resumes\n\nWHAT SERVICE DOES FOR YOUR COMMUNITY:\nYour neighborhood, school, and city have real needs. There are elderly people who cannot get groceries. Children who need tutors. Organizations that need volunteers. If everyone waited for someone else to serve, nothing would get done.\n\nSERVICE CHANGES YOUR PERSPECTIVE:\nWhen you volunteer at a homeless shelter, mentor younger kids, or help clean up your neighborhood, you see your own life differently. Your problems get smaller. Your gratitude gets larger.\n\nSERVICE IS NOT CHARITY — IT IS SOLIDARITY:\nServing your community is not about looking down at people who need help. It is about standing beside them. The best service happens when you see yourself in the people you are serving.\n\nSTARTING SMALL:\nYou do not need to start a non-profit or organize a movement. Start with one act per week:\n- Help a neighbor\n- Tutor a younger student\n- Clean up a block\n- Visit an elderly person\n- Volunteer at a local organization\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What is one need in your school or community you have noticed but walked past?\n- Have you ever served someone and felt genuinely good afterward? What happened?\n- What would you do if you had one free Saturday to help your community?',
    1, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0011-0002-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000011',
    'Finding Your Cause',
    E'FINDING YOUR CAUSE\n\nYou will serve with more passion and persistence when you are connected to something you genuinely care about.\n\nEVERY MAN NEEDS A CAUSE:\nBeyond personal goals — money, career, relationships — every man of substance is connected to something beyond himself. A cause gives your life a north star.\n\nHOW TO FIND YOUR CAUSE:\nAsk yourself:\n1. What injustice makes you angry? (Anger at a problem is often the seed of your calling)\n2. What need in your community do you see that others ignore?\n3. What have you personally experienced or overcome that you want to help others with?\n4. Who do you feel most drawn to serve? (Children? The elderly? Men in prison? At-risk youth?)\n\nCAUSES THAT NEED YOUNG MEN:\n- Mentoring younger boys\n- Education and literacy programs\n- Food insecurity and hunger\n- Prison ministry and reentry support\n- Youth sports and athletic programs\n- Neighborhood beautification and safety\n- Environmental stewardship\n- Veterans'' support\n\nVOLUNTEERING AS EXPLORATION:\nYou do not need to commit to a cause for life. Volunteer in several different areas and see what resonates. What ignites something in you?\n\nSKILLS-BASED SERVICE:\nRather than just giving time, give your skills:\n- Graphic design for a non-profit\n- Tech support for elderly neighbors\n- Photography for a community event\n- Social media management for a small org\n\nCAUSE + SKILLS = IMPACT:\nWhen you combine your unique abilities with a genuine cause, you create lasting change that could not exist without you specifically.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What injustice or community need stirs something in you?\n- What skills do you have that could serve a cause?\n- What is one organization in your city that is doing work you admire?',
    2, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0011-0003-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000011',
    'Civic Engagement & Your Voice',
    E'CIVIC ENGAGEMENT & YOUR VOICE\n\nYou live in a democracy. Whether or not you engage with it, it will affect you. You might as well have a seat at the table.\n\nWHAT IS CIVIC ENGAGEMENT?\nCivic engagement is active participation in the life of your community and society — from local issues to national ones.\n\nLEVELS OF CIVIC ENGAGEMENT:\n- Staying informed: Reading news, understanding issues that affect your community\n- Voting: Your most fundamental right and responsibility as a citizen\n- Community meetings: School board, city council, neighborhood associations\n- Advocacy: Speaking up for issues you care about — in person and online\n- Running for office: At any level, including student government\n- Volunteering for campaigns or causes\n\nWHY YOUR VOTE MATTERS:\nIn many local elections, a few hundred votes determine who wins. City council members, school board members, and local judges have direct impact on your daily life — and many elections are decided by small margins.\n\nRegister to vote as soon as you turn 18. Most states allow pre-registration at 16 or 17.\n\nSTAYING INFORMED:\n- Follow trusted local news sources\n- Be skeptical of social media "news" — check multiple sources\n- Understand the difference between facts and opinions\n- Know your representatives (federal, state, and local)\n\nFINDING YOUR POLITICAL VOICE:\nYou do not have to belong to a party or adopt a set ideology. Develop your own informed views by:\n- Learning about different perspectives\n- Asking questions\n- Engaging respectfully with people who disagree\n\nLOCAL MATTERS MORE THAN NATIONAL:\nPresidential elections get all the attention, but your daily life is shaped most by local decisions: where schools get funded, how police operate, what gets built in your neighborhood.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- Are you registered to vote, or will you be when you turn 18?\n- What local issue affects your community that you want to know more about?\n- What is one way you can make your voice heard in your school or community?',
    3, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0011-0004-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000011',
    'Leading Change in Your Community',
    E'LEADING CHANGE IN YOUR COMMUNITY\n\nYou do not have to wait until you are older, wealthier, or more established to lead change. Start now.\n\nYOUTH-LED CHANGE IS REAL:\n- Malala Yousafzai began advocating for girls'' education at 11\n- Greta Thunberg launched a global climate movement at 15\n- Countless young men have organized neighborhood clean-ups, started tutoring programs, and built community organizations before graduating high school\n\nAge is not a barrier to impact. Commitment is what matters.\n\nSTARTING A COMMUNITY PROJECT:\n1. Identify the problem clearly: What specifically needs to change?\n2. Research: What is already being done? What has worked elsewhere?\n3. Build a team: You cannot do it alone. Find others who care.\n4. Start small: A proof-of-concept project is better than a grand plan that never launches.\n5. Seek support: Local businesses, churches, community organizations, and grants all fund youth-led initiatives.\n6. Measure impact: Know how you will know if you are making a difference.\n\nSKILLS COMMUNITY LEADERSHIP BUILDS:\n- Project management\n- Public speaking and communication\n- Fundraising\n- Team coordination\n- Problem solving\n- Resilience (things will go wrong — keep going)\n\nFINDING SUPPORT:\n- Talk to your mentor about your idea\n- Find local non-profits who support youth leadership\n- Apply for youth grants and competitions\n- Look for adult allies — people with resources and connections who believe in you\n\nYOUR COMMUNITY NEEDS YOU SPECIFICALLY:\nNot a generic volunteer — you. Your story, your knowledge of the neighborhood, your relationships, your perspective. That is irreplaceable.\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What change do you most want to see in your community?\n- What skills and resources do you already have that could contribute to that change?\n- Who could you bring into a project with you?',
    4, 20, NOW()
  ),


-- =============================================
-- TRACK 12: FAITH & PURPOSE
-- =============================================

  (
    '44444444-0012-0001-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000012',
    'What Do You Believe?',
    E'WHAT DO YOU BELIEVE?\n\nYour beliefs about God, yourself, and the world are the most foundational things in your life. They deserve careful examination.\n\nWHY BELIEFS MATTER:\nYour beliefs determine your values. Your values determine your decisions. Your decisions determine your character. Your character determines your destiny.\n\nThis is not a chain you want to leave unexamined.\n\nTHREE FOUNDATIONAL BELIEF QUESTIONS:\n1. Is there a God, and does He care about me personally?\n2. What is the purpose of my life?\n3. What happens after death, and does it change how I should live now?\n\nThese are not questions with easy answers. But serious men ask them.\n\nFAITH IS NOT BLIND:\nMany of the most intelligent people in human history — scientists, philosophers, historians, leaders — held deep faith. Seeking evidence for what you believe is not a sign of weak faith. It is a sign of an honest mind.\n\nDOUBT IS PART OF FAITH:\nEvery person of genuine faith has wrestled with doubt. Doubt that drives you to seek is healthy. Doubt that drives you to give up is different. Ask your questions. Seek answers. Do not pretend.\n\nRESPECTING OTHERS'' BELIEFS:\nThis track reflects the faith tradition at the heart of this program — rooted in Christian principles. But men of all backgrounds are welcome. Your spiritual journey is your own. Engage with these questions honestly from wherever you are.\n\nSPIRITUAL PRACTICES THAT BUILD CHARACTER (ACROSS TRADITIONS):\n- Prayer and meditation: Quieting the mind, seeking guidance\n- Scripture or sacred text study: Ancient wisdom applied to modern life\n- Community worship: Connection with others on a similar journey\n- Fasting: Training your body to serve your will\n- Service: Living out beliefs in action\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What do you currently believe about God?\n- Where did your beliefs come from, and have you examined them yourself?\n- What spiritual practice, if any, gives you peace or clarity?',
    1, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0012-0002-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000012',
    'Living with Purpose',
    E'LIVING WITH PURPOSE\n\nA man with purpose is dangerous — in the best possible way. He cannot be easily distracted, manipulated, or stopped.\n\nWHAT IS PURPOSE?\nPurpose is the reason you get up in the morning beyond obligation. It is the answer to "Why does my life matter?" It gives you direction when the path is unclear and fuel when the work is hard.\n\nPURPOSE IS DISCOVERED, NOT ASSIGNED:\nNo one else can tell you your purpose. But there are clues:\n- What makes you come alive?\n- What need do you keep noticing that others walk past?\n- What would you do even if you were never paid for it?\n- What would you want written on your gravestone?\n\nTHE DANGER OF A PURPOSELESS LIFE:\nMen without purpose are easily filled by other things — substances, thrill-seeking, gaming, destructive relationships. The emptiness of purposelessness is real, and something will always fill it. Choose what fills it intentionally.\n\nSHORT-TERM vs. LONG-TERM PURPOSE:\nYour purpose will evolve. At 16, your purpose might be to become the best student, son, or athlete you can be. At 25, it grows. At 35, deeper still. Purpose is not a destination — it is a direction.\n\nPURPOSE REQUIRES SACRIFICE:\nLiving on purpose means saying no to things that are not your purpose. It means choosing the harder path because it leads somewhere meaningful. Every great purpose costs something.\n\nFAITH AND PURPOSE:\nMany men find that their deepest sense of purpose is connected to their faith — a calling that feels given rather than chosen. Whether or not you share that framework, every man needs to answer: what am I here for?\n\nWRITING YOUR PERSONAL MISSION STATEMENT:\nA personal mission statement in one or two sentences: what you are, what you do, and who you do it for.\nExample: "I am a man of faith and discipline who builds other men up and provides for those who depend on me."\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What is your current answer to "What am I here for?"\n- What is one purpose-driven goal you want to achieve in the next five years?\n- Write a draft of your personal mission statement.',
    2, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0012-0003-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000012',
    'Character Under Pressure',
    E'CHARACTER UNDER PRESSURE\n\nAnyone can have values when life is easy. Your true character is revealed when the cost of integrity is high.\n\nWHAT PRESSURE REVEALS:\nPressure does not build character — it reveals it. The character that shows up under stress, temptation, and adversity is the character that has been forming through your daily choices.\n\nTYPES OF CHARACTER TESTS:\n- Temptation: The opportunity to benefit at someone else''s expense, or by compromising your values\n- Adversity: Difficulty that challenges your persistence, faith, and resolve\n- Success: Prosperity that tests your humility, generosity, and gratitude\n- Loneliness: Isolation that tests your conviction when no one is watching\n\nFAITH AS AN ANCHOR:\nMany men report that it is their faith that holds them when everything else fails. A conviction that God is sovereign, that your life has meaning, and that your choices matter beyond what you can see — this is a powerful stabilizer in chaos.\n\nTHE JOSEPH PRINCIPLE:\nJoseph (from the Bible) was sold into slavery by his own brothers, falsely imprisoned, and forgotten. Yet he never became bitter, never abandoned his integrity, and eventually rose to lead a nation. His faithfulness in small, invisible, painful moments prepared him for massive impact.\n\nYour current pressures are preparing you for something. Do not waste them.\n\nRESILIENCE IS BUILT, NOT GIVEN:\n- Every difficulty you get through strengthens your capacity for the next one\n- Failure is not the end. How you respond to failure is what defines you.\n- Surround yourself with people who reinforce the person you are trying to become\n\nKEEPING YOUR VALUES WHEN IT COSTS YOU:\n- When doing the right thing means losing a friend, losing money, or losing status — that is when your values are real\n- Every time you choose integrity under pressure, you make the next right choice easier\n\nREFLECTION:\n- Describe a time you held your values under pressure. How did it feel afterward?\n- What is a current situation testing your character?\n- What principle or faith conviction helps you most when things get hard?',
    3, 20, NOW()
  ),
  (
    '44444444-0012-0004-0000-000000000000',
    '33333333-0000-0000-0000-000000000012',
    'Your Legacy: What Will You Leave Behind?',
    E'YOUR LEGACY: WHAT WILL YOU LEAVE BEHIND?\n\nThe best time to think about your legacy is now, while you still have time to build it.\n\nWHAT IS A LEGACY?\nA legacy is what remains after you are gone — not just money or possessions, but impact. The lives you touched. The character you modeled. The things you built. The people you raised up.\n\nLEGACY STARTS IN ORDINARY MOMENTS:\nLegacy is not built in one great moment. It is built in ten thousand small ones:\n- How you treated people who could do nothing for you\n- Whether you showed up when it was hard\n- What you said when no one was watching\n- How you responded to failure and to success\n\nTHE GENERATIONAL LENS:\nYour choices affect people who do not exist yet. Your children and grandchildren will inherit your habits, patterns, values, and wounds — or your healing and strength. The chain you break today does not bind the next generation.\n\nTHE DASH:\nOn every gravestone there is a dash between the year of birth and the year of death. That dash is your entire life. What will fill yours?\n\nLETTER TO YOUR FUTURE SELF:\nOne of the most powerful exercises for legacy-building: write a letter to yourself at age 40. Describe who you are, what you have built, who you have loved, and what you stand for. Then work backward — what do you need to do today to become that person?\n\nMENTORSHIP AS LEGACY:\nThe reason Iron Sharpens Iron exists is that someone believed the best investment is in the next generation. Your mentors are building their legacy through you. One day, you will build yours through someone younger.\n\nTHE FOUNDATION OF A LASTING LEGACY:\n- Character that holds under any circumstance\n- Faith that gives meaning to suffering and purpose to success\n- Love that is consistent, patient, and sacrificial\n- Service that puts others above yourself\n\nREFLECTION:\n- What do you want people to say about you at your funeral?\n- What is one pattern from your family history you want to be the last generation to carry?\n- What is the most important thing you want to pass on to the next generation?',
    4, 20, NOW()
  )
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
